description: From Latin obtrūdō (“thrust off or against”), from ob- (“ob-”) + trūdō (“thrust”).

verbs.description: obtrude (third-person singular simple present obtrudes, present participle obtruding, simple past and past participle obtruded)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To proffer (something) by force; to impose (something) on someone or into some area. [from 16th c.]
examples: By which we may see, that they who are not called to Counsell, can have no good Counsell in such cases to obtrude.

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To become apparent in an unwelcome way, to be forcibly imposed; to jut in, to intrude (on or into). [from 16th c.]
examples: Sometimes I dreamed strangely of disturbed earth, and of hair, still golden and living, obtruded through the coffin-chinks.

entries.meaning: (reflexive) To impose (oneself) on others; to cut in. [from 17th c.]
examples: She obtruded herself upon the Queen; she protested her party views; she asked for petty favours, and attributed the refusals to the influence of Abigail.
